        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='5394' hidden='true' id='6' story-point-id='2' type-v2='text' w='73524' x='8366' y='18465'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true'>ANALYSIS OF CUSTOMERS CONCENTRATION BY GEOGRAPHICAL AREAS</run>
            <run> (STATES)</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='40871' hidden='true' id='7' story-point-id='2' type-v2='text' w='17126' x='3445' y='36100'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontalignment='0' fontsize='12'>CONCLUSIONS</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontsize='12'>:</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontsize='12'>-  California is the state with the most amount of customer</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontsize='12'>- Washington is the state with the least amoun of customers</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontalignment='0' fontsize='12'>- There doesn&apos;t seem to be a pattern to geographical distribution like for example coastal vs inland</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='7261' hidden='true' id='8' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='59941' x='14764' y='14627'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true'>ANALYSIS OF THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN CUSTOMER LIFETIME VALUE AND INCOME</run>
            <run> (and identified by policy type)</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='56017' hidden='true' id='9' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='20965' x='78937' y='27490'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' fontalignment='0'>OBSERVATIONS</run>
            <run fontalignment='0'>:

- The regression line and scatter plot are nearly horizontal

- There&apos;s a very week relationship between Income and CLV

- As income increases CLV only increases marginally

- The trend lines are only slightly positive with barely any slope

- Income is not a strong predictor of CLV</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='7469' id='10' story-point-id='4' type-v2='text' w='50000' x='34646' y='18880'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true'>Analysis of the relationship between Total Claim Amount and Vehicle Size</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='43154' id='11' story-point-id='4' type-v2='text' w='57087' x='33858' y='34336'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontalignment='0'>Observations:

- The median and interquartile ranges are similar for all vehicle sizes which indicates there&apos;s no major difference in total claim amounts between vehicle sizes

- The data is widely spread and the claim amounts vary greatly accross all categories as shown by the numerous ooutliers

- There are many high value outliers, specially for large and midsize vehicles

- Most claims can be found in the region of under 1000$</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='5705' hidden='true' id='12' story-point-id='1' type-v2='text' w='64173' x='15846' y='37137'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run bold='true' italic='true' underline='true'>MARKETING CUSTOMER VALUE ANALYSIS</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
      </zones>
      <simple-id uuid='{24997B56-1AE6-46A4-A28D-70B8988C8C6C}' />
    </dashboard>
